What is claimed is: 

       1. A system for identification of command injection attacks, the system comprising:
 one or more devices connected to a network; 
 a non-transitory memory device, said non-transitory memory device having modules of instruction code stored thereon; 
 an execution platform executing executable products, said execution platform is connected to said one or more devices via said network, wherein said one or more devices are configured to provide execution commands to said execution platform; 
 one or more processors associated with said memory device, wherein at least one processor of said one or more processors is configured to execute the modules of instruction code, whereupon execution of said modules of instruction code said at least one processor is further configured to: 
 analyze execution commands provided to said execution platform to identify input provisioning events or execution events; 
 in response to identifying a potential input provisioning event, determine that an input of the potential input provisioning event includes a command separator and an executable product, wherein the input of the potential input provisioning event is received from said network, wherein the command separator is a character or combination of characters configured to separate between two commands; 
 in response to said determining that the input includes the command separator and the executable product, record a suspicious record event; 
 in response to identifying a potential execution event, determine that an execution command of the potential execution event correlates to the suspicious record event, wherein the execution command is configured to be executed by the potential execution event; 
 in response to said determining that the execution command correlates to the suspicious record event, flag the execution command as a command injection attack; and 
 perform a remedial action with respect to the flagged command injection attack prior to attempting to execute the execution command by said execution platform. 



       2. The system of  claim 1  further comprises:
 a suspicious events database configured to retain a list of suspicious record events; 
 wherein said at least one processor is further configured to: 
 in response to flagging a command injection attack, store the command injection attack in said suspicious events database; 
 wherein the remedial action comprises: 
 inspecting whether the second execution command is associated with an event retained in said suspicious events database; and 
 in response to identifying that the second execution command is associated with an event retained in said suspicious events database, preventing said execution platform from executing the second execution command. 



       3. The system of  claim 1 , wherein the remedial action comprises at least one of:
 reporting command injection attack to a user; and preventing execution of the flagged execution command. 



       4. The system of  claim 1 , wherein the suspicious record event comprises the command separator, the executable product, and a timestamp of the potential input provisioning event. 


       5. The system of  claim 4 , wherein a correlation determination of said determining that the execution command correlates to the suspicious record event, is time-dependent and based on a correlation between the timestamp of the potential input provisioning event and a timing of the potential execution event. 


       6. The system of  claim 4 , wherein said flagging the execution command is performed in response to identifying that recorded suspicious input event occurred within a predetermined time window prior to a timing of the potential execution event. 


       7. The system of  claim 4 , wherein said at least one processor is further configured to:
 identify that the execution command is a delayed execution command; 
 wherein said flagging the execution command as a command injection attack is performed in response to determining that the delayed execution command correlates to a recorded suspicious input event, regardless of the timestamp of the potential input provisioning event. 



       8. The system of  claim 1 , wherein the potential input provisioning event is an execution of a string generation function, wherein said determining that the input of the potential input provisioning event includes the command separator and the executable product is performed by a string manipulation hook function that is configured to analyze strings that are generated using string generation functions. 


       9. The system of  claim 8 , wherein said at least one processor is further configured to:
 determine an origin of input strings provided to the string generation function to identify whether the input strings are obtained from one or more read-only memory regions; and 
 add the input strings to a whitelist table to track input strings obtained from the one or more read-only memory regions. 



       10. The system of  claim 8 , wherein said at least one processor is further configured to set up triggers to activate the string manipulation hook function upon an execution of a specific string generation function based on predetermined conditions, wherein the predetermined conditions comprise at least one of network data receipt events, or execution environment state changes. 


       11. The system of  claim 8 , wherein said at least one processor is further configured to periodically activate the string manipulation hook function to analyze string generation events occurring within a predetermined time window. 


       12. The system of  claim 1 ,
 wherein said determining that the input of the potential input provisioning event includes the command separator and the executable product is performed by an input hook function; 
 wherein said determining that the execution command of the potential execution event correlates to the suspicious record event is performed by an execution hook function; 
 wherein said at least one processor is further configured to: 
 configure the input hook function to be invoked in response to the potential input provisioning event; and 
 configure the execution hook function to be invoked in response to the potential execution event. 



       13. A computer program product comprising a non-transitory computer readable storage medium retaining program instructions, which program instructions when read by a processor, cause the processor to perform:
 analyzing execution commands provided to an execution platform, the execution platform is executing executable products, the execution platform is connected to one or more devices via a network, wherein the one or more devices are configured to provide execution commands to the execution platform, wherein the execution platform is configured to identify input provisioning events or execution events; 
 in response to identifying a potential input provisioning event, determining that an input of the potential input provisioning event includes a command separator and an executable product, wherein the input of the potential input provisioning event is received from the network, wherein the command separator is a character or combination of characters configured to separate between two commands; 
 in response to said determining that the input includes the command separator and the executable product, recording a suspicious record event; 
 in response to identifying a potential execution event, determining that an execution command of the potential execution event correlates to the suspicious record event, wherein the execution command is configured to be executed by the potential execution event; 
 in response to said determining that the execution command correlates to the suspicious record event, flagging the execution command as a command injection attack; and 
 performing a remedial action with respect to the flagged command injection attack prior to attempting to execute the execution command by said execution platform. 



       14. A method comprising:
 analyzing execution commands provided to an execution platform, the execution platform is executing executable products, the execution platform is connected to one or more devices via a network, wherein the one or more devices are configured to provide execution commands to the execution platform, wherein the execution platform is configured to identify input provisioning events or execution events; 
